WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-GB

00:00:02.960 --> 00:00:07.160
Nashville, 'Music City',
where aspiring artists stake

00:00:07.160 --> 00:00:08.960
their claim for stardom.

00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:10.920
But is that American
dream here waking up

00:00:10.920 --> 00:00:14.800
to a new reality of corporate
investment, sky-high property

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:17.080
taxes, and a tourist boom?

00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:18.960
And can the musicians
who once hoped

00:00:18.960 --> 00:00:21.280
to turn their struggle
into success even

00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:23.320
afford to live here anymore?

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:26.080
Nashville has always been an
affordable place for musicians

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:27.720
to get their start.

00:00:27.720 --> 00:00:29.820
And I worry that we're
losing that affordability.

00:00:29.820 --> 00:00:33.680
And I find myself wondering
how many Garth Brooks out there

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:35.320
are not going to
make it and are not

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:37.675
going to come out and
grace us with their music

00:00:37.675 --> 00:00:39.800
because they couldn't come
here in the first place,

00:00:39.800 --> 00:00:41.467
because they couldn't
afford to be here.

00:00:41.467 --> 00:00:43.060
I remember when I
first moved here,

00:00:43.060 --> 00:00:46.600
and people would spend $300 to
crash on their friend's couch

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:47.880
or room.

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:52.280
And now we're talking $2,000,
$3,000, $4,000 a month to live.

00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:55.080
Many locals describe
the city's evolution

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:59.680
as a kind of Las Vegasication,
a shift towards spectacle,

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:02.840
commercialisation,
and mass entertainment

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:05.740
at the expense of authenticity.

00:01:05.740 --> 00:01:08.980
There were always tourists
going to the honky-tonks

00:01:08.980 --> 00:01:09.920
on Lower Broad.

00:01:09.920 --> 00:01:12.100
Tootsie's was one
of the most famous.

00:01:12.100 --> 00:01:15.780
We'd go see bands that
record labels wanted to sign.

00:01:15.780 --> 00:01:17.240
But you could still get in.

00:01:17.240 --> 00:01:20.500
You could still
get a beer for $2.

00:01:20.500 --> 00:01:24.720
And then I would say, about 10
years ago, it just exploded,

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:29.300
where every major artist has
their own honky-tonk and bar.

00:01:29.300 --> 00:01:32.180
You can be down there
on a Thursday morning,

00:01:32.180 --> 00:01:33.800
and there's a line.

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:36.580
They want you to come
in, get a bucket of beer,

00:01:36.580 --> 00:01:38.460
drink it, and get out.

00:01:38.460 --> 00:01:41.580
The drinking came along with the
music, but it was music first.

00:01:41.580 --> 00:01:43.700
Now there's more
of a crowd that's

00:01:43.700 --> 00:01:47.140
here to party and raise hell.

00:01:47.140 --> 00:01:50.920
It's a conscious decision of
what type of tourism you get.

00:01:50.920 --> 00:01:56.540
Authenticity sells,
and it's long-term.

00:01:56.540 --> 00:02:00.270
Flashy lights, that's temporary.

00:02:00.270 --> 00:02:03.600
The culture here used to
be grassroots, accessible,

00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:04.980
distinctly local.

00:02:04.980 --> 00:02:07.000
But that identity is evolving.

00:02:13.350 --> 00:02:17.710
The show Nashville, that became
not only nationally popular

00:02:17.710 --> 00:02:21.150
but internationally
popular, drove this kind

00:02:21.150 --> 00:02:24.150
of new wave of tourism.

00:02:24.150 --> 00:02:26.330
So you have the
corporate travel,

00:02:26.330 --> 00:02:29.470
the convention travel that was
fuelled by the new convention

00:02:29.470 --> 00:02:29.970
centre.

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:31.595
And then you have
the individual travel

00:02:31.595 --> 00:02:35.590
and us shifting to be called
the bachelorette capital

00:02:35.590 --> 00:02:36.585
of the world.

00:02:36.585 --> 00:02:38.210
You've got to have
the tourist dollars.

00:02:38.210 --> 00:02:40.710
But there's a way to
take in tourism money

00:02:40.710 --> 00:02:43.850
and then reinvest
it in the community.

00:02:43.850 --> 00:02:48.750
We had about $11bn in
visitor spending in 2024.

00:02:48.750 --> 00:02:54.350
It equates to about $3,600
of revenue that, otherwise,

00:02:54.350 --> 00:02:57.710
the citizens of Nashville would
have to cover in state and local

00:02:57.710 --> 00:02:58.330
taxes.

00:02:58.330 --> 00:03:02.090
So it really does have a
positive impact on households.

00:03:02.090 --> 00:03:06.790
It helps us to fund the services
that our community desperately

00:03:06.790 --> 00:03:08.310
needs.

00:03:08.310 --> 00:03:10.030
Many long-term
residents are already

00:03:10.030 --> 00:03:14.410
struggling to keep up with
rising costs in Trump's America.

00:03:14.410 --> 00:03:17.570
The question now is whether
Nashville's identity is still

00:03:17.570 --> 00:03:21.290
rooted in community
or in capitalism.

00:03:21.290 --> 00:03:22.930
Tax is a key issue.

00:03:22.930 --> 00:03:25.410
Republicans say
Tennessee's low-tax regime

00:03:25.410 --> 00:03:27.650
has been a big draw
for big companies

00:03:27.650 --> 00:03:30.730
like Amazon, Oracle,
and Starbucks.

00:03:30.730 --> 00:03:33.110
Residents might not
have to pay income tax,

00:03:33.110 --> 00:03:34.850
but Democrats say
this has pushed

00:03:34.850 --> 00:03:36.890
revenue raising
into other areas,

00:03:36.890 --> 00:03:40.030
like sales taxes
and property taxes.

00:03:40.030 --> 00:03:43.650
And that has left smaller
companies exposed.

00:03:43.650 --> 00:03:45.930
That's becoming
a real issue here

00:03:45.930 --> 00:03:48.970
in Nashville, Davidson
County, with the assessments

00:03:48.970 --> 00:03:50.350
that are skyrocketing.

00:03:50.350 --> 00:03:53.890
We've got businesses,
constituents that their tax

00:03:53.890 --> 00:03:56.570
bill is quadrupling.

00:03:56.570 --> 00:03:59.590
One business downtown,
Acme Feed and Seed,

00:03:59.590 --> 00:04:02.090
right there on First
Avenue and Broadway,

00:04:02.090 --> 00:04:07.130
their tax bill went from
$129,000 to over $600,000 in one

00:04:07.130 --> 00:04:08.510
year.

00:04:08.510 --> 00:04:11.990
As property valuations
rise, so do property taxes.

00:04:11.990 --> 00:04:14.710
And some lease agreements mean
it's the tenants rather than

00:04:14.710 --> 00:04:17.269
the owners who have to pay up.

00:04:17.269 --> 00:04:19.490
For business, you
need certainty.

00:04:19.490 --> 00:04:22.210
You've got to be able to rely
on the people working for you.

00:04:22.210 --> 00:04:25.450
You need to be able to have a
business plan and work the plan.

00:04:25.450 --> 00:04:29.460
You can't, overnight,
increase your taxes by 400%.

00:04:29.460 --> 00:04:31.930
Our tax code discriminates
against small businesses.

00:04:31.930 --> 00:04:34.190
It's really tough in this
environment right now.

00:04:34.190 --> 00:04:36.910
And a lot of that
hostility has been

00:04:36.910 --> 00:04:41.030
channelled into condemning the
mayor for increasing property

00:04:41.030 --> 00:04:42.270
taxes.

00:04:42.270 --> 00:04:45.070
The period from
2021 to 2025 just

00:04:45.070 --> 00:04:48.210
saw a leap in property
values countywide,

00:04:48.210 --> 00:04:50.410
we haven't seen
since I can recall.

00:04:50.410 --> 00:04:51.570
That's a challenge.

00:04:51.570 --> 00:04:54.110
And it's the only
way we can operate

00:04:54.110 --> 00:04:56.990
a city in the state of
Tennessee, in the United States,

00:04:56.990 --> 00:04:59.950
is that property
taxes are the largest

00:04:59.950 --> 00:05:04.190
portion of the revenue that
we have to keep our parks

00:05:04.190 --> 00:05:08.610
and libraries open, to fund our
schools, to fund our police.

00:05:08.610 --> 00:05:10.710
The construction of the
new football stadium

00:05:10.710 --> 00:05:13.070
has also raised tensions.

00:05:13.070 --> 00:05:15.990
They're building a new stadium
over there, a covered dome

00:05:15.990 --> 00:05:16.990
stadium.

00:05:16.990 --> 00:05:20.000
It's subsidised by the city.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.640
Oracle's building a
big campus over there.

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:26.160
It's subsidised by the city.

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:30.080
Amazon built two towers
that are subsidised...

00:05:30.080 --> 00:05:31.340
By the city.

00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:33.320
I know there's been
tension around the stadium

00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:36.100
and the push-and-pull of
tourism versus locals.

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:38.900
And it's something we see play
out in a number of places.

00:05:38.900 --> 00:05:43.120
There's this tourist versus
local that starts to happen.

00:05:43.120 --> 00:05:46.520
And I want to see it as a
both/and not an either/or.

00:05:46.520 --> 00:05:48.840
We can be investing in our
schools and our teachers

00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:51.720
and our affordability but
also building state-of-the-art

00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:55.200
buildings that draw people in
to help pay some of those bills.

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:57.500
Long-term residents are
feeling the squeeze.

00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:01.420
Housing costs have doubled since
2018, largely driven by luxury,

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:04.280
high-density development
that is transforming historic

00:06:04.280 --> 00:06:06.962
working-class neighbourhoods.

00:06:06.962 --> 00:06:08.920
Several of our artists,
in the past five years,

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:10.520
have moved back
to their hometowns

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:13.250
just because they couldn't
afford to live here anymore.

00:06:13.250 --> 00:06:16.820
People are coming to Tennessee
because of the low tax,

00:06:16.820 --> 00:06:18.180
the low regulation.

00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:20.160
There's no state income tax.

00:06:20.160 --> 00:06:23.460
We are a low tax-state for
multinational corporations

00:06:23.460 --> 00:06:24.080
and the rich.

00:06:24.080 --> 00:06:26.480
And we are a high-tax
state for working families.

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:30.380
Our tax code inevitably allows
multinational corporations,

00:06:30.380 --> 00:06:34.500
like FedEx, Amazon, and
Google, to muscle their way out

00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:38.140
of paying taxes, whereas small
business owners, including Acme,

00:06:38.140 --> 00:06:39.980
they are paying a
higher effective tax

00:06:39.980 --> 00:06:42.920
rate than the largest
companies in this country.

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:46.980
They're driving people out while
trying to recruit people left

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:49.340
and right to be in
the downtown area.

00:06:49.340 --> 00:06:52.480
The policies they're putting
in place are pushing them out.

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:54.670
Things that can be done
by a city and community

00:06:54.670 --> 00:06:57.740
- an example that we have
actually done here in Nashville

00:06:57.740 --> 00:07:02.260
- is creating housing that
provides subsidised housing

00:07:02.260 --> 00:07:05.100
for artists and musicians.

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:08.920
The challenge now is not just
sustaining economic momentum

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:12.500
but making sure the songwriters,
performers, and creatives

00:07:12.500 --> 00:07:15.660
who define Nashville's
global brand can continue

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:20.000
to live, work, and thrive in the
city they helped put on the map.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:21.760
You can't take these
things for granted.

00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:23.468
That's what we've
learned over the years,

00:07:23.468 --> 00:07:25.990
is you can't just assume that
'Music City' brand will be

00:07:25.990 --> 00:07:29.110
protected when it's becoming
harder and harder for musicians

00:07:29.110 --> 00:07:30.820
and artists to live here.

00:07:30.820 --> 00:07:31.990
And it's really...

00:07:31.990 --> 00:07:33.850
it is bigger than just the city.

00:07:33.850 --> 00:07:36.670
It's really a state,
council, and city problem.

00:07:36.670 --> 00:07:40.950
And they have to get together to
create a grander vision of where

00:07:40.950 --> 00:07:45.755
we're trying to go and all work
together to execute that vision.

00:07:45.755 --> 00:07:47.130
The mayor can't
do it on his own.

00:07:47.130 --> 00:07:48.750
The state can't do
it on their own.

00:07:48.750 --> 00:07:50.830
Council can't do
it on their own.

00:07:50.830 --> 00:07:53.790
And there's just been a total
lack of communication or vision

00:07:53.790 --> 00:07:59.030
in how we make sure
to protect this.

00:07:59.030 --> 00:08:01.950
From honky-tonks to high-rises,
Nashville's evolution

00:08:01.950 --> 00:08:04.750
tells a story, of
growth, opportunity,

00:08:04.750 --> 00:08:07.030
and unintended consequences.

00:08:07.030 --> 00:08:10.630
As the city continues to
expand, the challenge is clear,

00:08:10.630 --> 00:08:12.510
to preserve its
cultural identity

00:08:12.510 --> 00:08:15.310
and ensure that
prosperity is shared,

00:08:15.310 --> 00:08:18.250
because in Nashville, music
isn't just an industry,

00:08:18.250 --> 00:08:20.700
it's the foundation
of everything.

